WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:08.100
Hengrin readers, level one, The Missing Coins by John Escott

00:08.100 --> 00:18.920
Cop Bath is a very old city in England. It

00:18.920 --> 00:22.960
has a beautiful abbey. A lot of people visit

00:22.960 --> 00:28.000
the city every year. And in the summer there are

00:28.000 --> 00:30.900
always a lot of tourists in the streets.

00:32.400 --> 00:38.220
Heat and Carla are students in Bath. They like the

00:38.220 --> 00:41.600
city. Heat likes looking at the

00:41.600 --> 00:47.160
beautiful old buildings. Carla likes walking in the little streets.

00:48.540 --> 00:49.320
She often

00:49.320 --> 00:54.420
finds pretty little shops there and goes into them. Or

00:54.420 --> 00:56.180
she sits with heat in a

00:56.180 --> 01:03.600
cafe and watches the tourists. It's a Saturday in summer

01:03.600 --> 01:05.700
and a hot afternoon.

01:07.040 --> 01:09.900
There are a lot of tourists in the city today.

01:11.020 --> 01:19.300
People from many countries are going into the

01:19.300 --> 01:26.660
way from the tourists. Carla says, okay. Heat says, he

01:26.660 --> 01:29.900
likes being with Carla. They walk

01:29.900 --> 01:35.560
away from the abbey. After some time they are in

01:35.560 --> 01:39.240
a little street behind the abbey. This is

01:39.240 --> 01:44.860
pretty, Carla says. There are only two or three tourists

01:44.860 --> 01:48.140
in this street. The shops have

01:48.140 --> 01:54.900
small windows. Some houses have pretty little gardens. It's quiet

01:54.900 --> 01:57.360
here but Pete and Carla

01:57.360 --> 02:04.340
can hear music. Look, Pete says, that man is playing

02:04.340 --> 02:09.660
a flute. Let's go and listen. They walk

02:09.660 --> 02:14.040
across the street and watch the man. Four or five

02:14.040 --> 02:17.840
people are listening. Why is he playing

02:17.840 --> 02:22.980
here? Carla asks. There aren't many tourists in this street.

02:24.040 --> 02:27.680
No, Pete says. And there are only

02:27.680 --> 02:33.600
three or four coins in his hat. Heat and Carla

02:33.600 --> 02:44.980
listen to the flute player. The tune is green

02:44.980 --> 02:51.740
man's hat. Pete takes her hand. Let's go, Carla. He

02:51.740 --> 02:55.140
says to her. Let's see the shops in the next

02:55.140 --> 03:03.160
street. Okay, Carla says. They walk away. The flute player

03:03.160 --> 03:05.920
watches them but his tune green

03:05.920 --> 03:12.000
sleeves doesn't stop. He isn't a very good flute player,

03:12.660 --> 03:15.800
Pete says. But it's a good tune.

03:17.180 --> 03:21.040
There were only four coins in his hat, Carla says.

03:22.380 --> 03:25.900
That's because he isn't very good, Pete says.

03:26.700 --> 03:31.660
And he's playing in the wrong street. The tourists are

03:31.660 --> 03:32.440
near the abbey.

03:32.440 --> 03:39.260
They walk to the next street. They find a little

03:39.260 --> 03:43.400
shop there. There are some old coins and stamps

03:43.400 --> 03:49.500
in the shop window. They come from many countries. Let's

03:49.500 --> 04:02.420
go in here, Carla says. It's an interesting

04:02.420 --> 04:07.440
call. Go in and an old man watches them. He

04:07.440 --> 04:13.180
is the shopkeeper. Good afternoon, he says.

04:14.290 --> 04:21.300
Good afternoon, Carla says. Hi, Pete says. What can I

04:21.300 --> 04:23.840
do for you? The shopkeeper says.

04:24.820 --> 04:30.200
Can we look at the stamps? Pete asks. The shopkeeper

04:30.200 --> 04:31.200
looks at them.

04:32.180 --> 04:40.560
Okay, he says. Do you collect stamps? No, but I'm

04:40.560 --> 04:43.560
going to start collecting them, Pete says.

04:44.520 --> 04:53.120
They're interesting. Yes, they are, the shopkeeper says. Pete looks

04:53.120 --> 04:54.720
at some stamps from Canada

04:55.100 --> 05:00.660
and some stamps from South America. These are beautiful stamps,

05:01.300 --> 05:04.000
he says. The shopkeeper

05:04.000 --> 05:10.600
stands near Pete and watches him. He isn't happy, Carla

05:10.600 --> 05:15.440
thinks. Why? We aren't going to steal stamps.

05:17.040 --> 05:22.580
She looks at some coins. Are these coins very old?

05:23.160 --> 05:24.800
Carla asks the old man.

05:25.600 --> 05:32.280
They're 300 years old, says the shopkeeper. They're very valuable.

05:32.980 --> 05:35.640
Every coin in my shop is

05:35.640 --> 05:41.580
valuable. A girl is working in the shop, too. She

05:41.580 --> 05:54.780
looks at Carla. Carla smiles, but the girl

05:54.780 --> 05:58.420
suddenly they hear a telephone in the room behind the

05:58.420 --> 06:02.180
shop. The shopkeeper doesn't answer it for a

06:02.180 --> 06:07.020
minute. Then he looks at the girl and she looks

06:07.020 --> 06:11.760
at him. They don't speak, but Carla understands.

06:13.020 --> 06:16.780
The shopkeeper doesn't speak, but he is saying to the

06:16.780 --> 06:19.380
girl, watch these students.

06:21.580 --> 06:25.980
Excuse me, he says to Carla and Pete, and he

06:25.980 --> 06:27.340
goes into the back room.

06:29.460 --> 06:34.360
Pete is looking at the stamps. Come and see these,

06:34.620 --> 06:36.100
Carla, he says.

06:37.440 --> 06:42.160
They're in South America. I want to start collecting them,

06:43.600 --> 06:48.560
but Carla doesn't like the people in this shop. They

06:48.560 --> 06:52.320
aren't very friendly, and she wants to look at the

06:52.320 --> 06:52.680
city.

06:54.460 --> 07:01.720
They're very expensive, she says. Let's go, Pete. The girl

07:01.720 --> 07:04.460
watches them, and then she smiles.

07:05.820 --> 07:10.720
She's happy because we're going, Carla thinks. But why?

07:12.140 --> 07:15.900
Pete and Carla go back into the big streets with

07:15.900 --> 07:20.120
the tourists. Carla is happy now because they are

07:20.120 --> 07:25.060
not in the shop, but the sun is hot and

07:25.060 --> 07:30.060
Pete wants a drink. Let's go to a cafe near

07:30.060 --> 07:30.740
the abbey,

07:30.740 --> 07:36.060
he says. He wanted the stamps from South America, but

07:36.060 --> 07:37.120
he doesn't say this.

07:38.700 --> 07:43.460
There are tables outside the cafe. Pete and Carla sit

07:43.460 --> 07:47.060
down. There are a lot of people in the cafe.

07:48.720 --> 07:54.200
Can we go into the abbey next? Carla asks. He

07:54.200 --> 07:56.340
wants the stamps from South America,

07:56.340 --> 07:59.400
she thinks. But they're very expensive.

08:01.360 --> 08:07.380
I want a drink first, Pete says. Okay, Carla says,

08:07.860 --> 08:12.040
and she smiles at him. Pete smiles at her too.

08:13.700 --> 08:18.600
After a minute or two, they hear, hey, there you

08:18.600 --> 08:23.700
are. Pete and Carla look up. It's the old man

08:23.700 --> 08:24.440
in the shop.

08:25.520 --> 08:30.880
What does he want? Pete says. I don't know, Carla

08:30.880 --> 08:34.420
says, but he's angry. What's wrong?

08:35.720 --> 08:40.460
The shopkeeper comes to the cafe. He is very angry.

08:41.560 --> 08:46.180
Where are my coins? He says, your coins,

08:46.740 --> 08:53.400
Carla says. I don't understand. They're missing, the shopkeeper says.

08:54.320 --> 08:55.880
Did you steal them?

08:57.120 --> 09:01.980
Carla and Pete are surprised. The people at the tables

09:01.980 --> 09:03.980
near them are surprised too.

09:04.840 --> 09:09.960
They watch the two friends and the old man. Stealing

09:09.960 --> 09:15.400
your coins? No, Carla says. Her face is hot

09:15.400 --> 09:21.600
red. We didn't steal any coins or stamps, Pete says.

09:22.340 --> 09:26.060
What are you saying? He is angry now.

09:27.420 --> 09:33.220
You've got my coins, the shopkeeper says. The coins are

09:33.220 --> 09:36.520
missing and this isn't the first time.

09:37.340 --> 09:42.080
Some coins were missing last week. Some students have been

09:42.080 --> 09:43.500
too, I think.

09:44.380 --> 09:48.940
Do you see the students with the coins? Pete says.

09:50.040 --> 09:51.900
The old man doesn't answer.

09:54.040 --> 09:58.420
A policeman walks down the streets to the cafe. He

09:58.420 --> 10:01.080
watches Carla and Pete and the shopkeeper.

10:02.320 --> 10:09.620
Then he says, what's wrong? These two students came into

10:09.620 --> 10:11.700
my shop, the shopkeeper says.

10:12.420 --> 10:16.320
I went to the back room and answered the telephone.

10:17.160 --> 10:19.860
Then I went back into the shop.

10:20.620 --> 10:25.280
Some valuable coins were missing and the two students were

10:25.280 --> 10:26.500
not in the shop.

10:27.960 --> 10:33.000
The policeman looks at Pete and Carla. What do you

10:33.000 --> 10:34.640
say? He asks.

10:35.620 --> 10:40.880
Yes, we went into the shop, Carla says. We wanted

10:40.880 --> 10:42.020
to look at the stamps.

10:43.420 --> 10:49.060
But we didn't steal them, Pete says. And we didn't

10:49.060 --> 10:49.940
take the coins.

10:51.520 --> 10:56.240
Were there many people in the shop? The policeman asks.

10:57.220 --> 10:59.520
No, the shopkeeper says.

11:00.430 --> 11:06.100
Only these two students and Tracy. Tracy works in my

11:06.100 --> 11:08.700
shop. She doesn't steal coins.

11:10.360 --> 11:13.360
How do you know? asks the policeman.

11:15.340 --> 11:19.360
I looked in her bag and pockets today, the shopkeeper

11:19.360 --> 11:23.020
says. And I looked in them last week.

11:24.340 --> 11:29.780
You can look in my bag, Carla says. And you

11:29.780 --> 11:32.520
can look in my pockets, Pete says.

11:33.880 --> 11:40.920
The shopkeeper is surprised. Can I? He says. Please look.

11:41.840 --> 11:47.540
Please look now, Carla says. We didn't steal any coins.

11:48.640 --> 11:49.980
She gives him her bag.

11:51.240 --> 11:56.220
The shopkeeper looks in Carla's bag and in their pockets.

11:57.440 --> 11:59.420
The people at the tables near them

11:59.420 --> 12:03.820
watch him. Is he going to find the coins, they

12:03.820 --> 12:07.900
think? But he finds no coins or stamps.

12:09.480 --> 12:15.740
We didn't steal the coins, Pete says. And now you

12:15.740 --> 12:16.400
know that.

12:18.400 --> 12:25.340
I'm sorry, the shopkeeper says. I was wrong, but I

12:25.340 --> 12:29.140
don't understand it. Where are the coins?

12:30.900 --> 12:35.860
Then the old man goes back to his shop. He

12:35.860 --> 12:39.260
isn't very happy, Pete says to the policeman.

12:41.220 --> 12:47.400
Coins are very small, the policeman says. Perhaps they're in

12:47.400 --> 12:49.820
the shop, but he can't see them.

12:51.420 --> 12:56.420
Some young people start to play music. A girl plays

12:56.420 --> 12:57.040
a flute.

12:58.460 --> 13:02.740
Who didn't steal any coins? Carla says to the policeman.

13:04.020 --> 13:06.520
I know, the policeman says.

13:08.260 --> 13:12.520
Carla listens to the music. It is green sleeves.

13:14.100 --> 13:19.520
Where did I hear that? She thinks. And then she

13:19.520 --> 13:22.720
remembers the flute player near the coin and

13:22.720 --> 13:29.900
stamp shop. He played that tune, she remembers. Pete is

13:29.900 --> 13:30.780
watching her face.

13:32.140 --> 13:36.060
What is it? He asks her. What's wrong?

13:37.440 --> 13:43.780
I know now, she says. The missing coins. I know

13:43.780 --> 13:44.560
the answer.

13:45.620 --> 13:51.400
Do you? Pete says. What is it? Come with me,

13:52.020 --> 13:53.920
she says to Pete and the policeman.

13:54.760 --> 13:59.840
We're going to find the man with the flute. Which

13:59.840 --> 14:02.160
man? The policeman says.

14:03.580 --> 14:06.880
He plays in the street near the old man's shop,

14:07.600 --> 14:07.960
Pete says.

14:09.380 --> 14:13.980
Then Carla, Pete and the policeman run to the stamp

14:13.980 --> 14:14.940
and coin shop.

14:16.220 --> 14:22.420
Hey, you, Carla says. The flute player is going to

14:22.420 --> 14:25.720
walk away, but the policeman stops him.

14:26.480 --> 14:31.400
Wait, the policeman says. We want to speak to you.

14:32.620 --> 14:38.820
The man wants to run now. I'm going home, he

14:38.820 --> 14:42.960
says. No, wait, the policeman says.

14:43.780 --> 14:49.920
He looks at Carla. You have the coins, Carla says

14:49.920 --> 14:50.920
to the flute player.

14:51.700 --> 14:57.300
No, the man says. He starts to run away, but

14:57.300 --> 14:59.160
the policeman stops him again.

15:00.260 --> 15:05.280
How did he do it? He tasks Carla. It was

15:05.280 --> 15:08.060
the girl in the shop, Carla says.

15:08.860 --> 15:14.760
We looked at some stamps, remember? And the shopkeeper was

15:14.760 --> 15:17.340
on the telephone in the room at the back.

15:19.120 --> 15:23.360
But how did the flute player get the coins? The

15:23.360 --> 15:24.380
policeman asks.

15:25.120 --> 15:32.640
Yes, Pete says. I don't understand. He was outside the

15:32.640 --> 15:34.240
window, Carla says.

15:34.950 --> 15:40.040
The girl went to the window with the coins. But

15:40.040 --> 15:43.500
there were people in the street, Pete says.

15:44.300 --> 15:50.320
Yes, perhaps people watched her, Carla says. But the coins

15:50.320 --> 15:53.480
went into the flute player's hat.

15:54.460 --> 15:58.200
The coins were valuable, but the people in the street

15:58.200 --> 15:59.660
didn't know that.

16:01.080 --> 16:05.740
The girl and the flute player were very clever, Pete

16:05.740 --> 16:06.080
says.

16:07.400 --> 16:11.140
But now they're coming with me to the police station,

16:11.760 --> 16:13.140
the policeman says.

16:14.480 --> 16:17.120
He takes the coins from the flute player.

16:18.600 --> 16:21.640
After some time, a police car arrives.

16:22.820 --> 16:25.700
It takes the girl and the flute player to the

16:25.700 --> 16:26.560
police station.

16:28.280 --> 16:34.280
Thank you, the shopkeeper says to Carla. The coins are

16:34.280 --> 16:37.640
valuable. I want to say thank you.

16:38.540 --> 16:42.420
What can I give you? Carla smiles.

16:44.160 --> 16:47.900
Give Pete the stamps from South America, she says.

16:48.760 --> 16:51.980
Then he can start his stamp collecting today.

16:53.300 --> 16:55.420
Pete gives her a big smile.

16:56.760 --> 17:00.840
Thanks, Carla, he says. I love you.

